First, let's find the symmetric difference (A⊕B) and the intersection (A∩B) of the two sets A and B.

A⊕B = (A∪B) - (A∩B) = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {2, 3} = {1, 4}
B⊕A = (B∪A) - (B∩A) = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {2, 3} = {1, 4} (Note that symmetric difference is commutative)

A∩B = {2, 3}

Now, let's find the Cartesian products (A⊕B) x (A∩B) and (B⊕A) x (A∩B).

(A⊕B) x (A∩B) = {1, 4} x {2, 3} = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

(B⊕A) x (A∩B) = {1, 4} x {2, 3} = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

As we can see, (A⊕B) x (A∩B) = (B⊕A) x (A∩B), which means that the symmetric difference of two sets is commutative with respect to Cartesian product in this case. However, this does not prove that it is always commutative for all cases.
